29:38.477 --> 29:39.444 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David?

29:39.478 --> 29:40.779 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

29:40.812 --> 29:42.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, the Democrats had the
better convention
by a long way.

29:42.180 --> 29:45.984 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's rare we see the gap so big,
frankly.

29:46.018 --> 29:47.953 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They controlled the debate.

29:47.986 --> 29:50.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump tried to set up
this debate where
it was going to be globalists
vs. nationalists,

29:50.989 --> 29:52.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the Republicans were going
to be the nationalists.

29:52.758 --> 29:56.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, if anything, the Democrats
looked more
patriotic and more nationalist
at the end

29:56.395 --> 29:57.896 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of these two.

29:57.929 --> 29:59.865 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so that was a big win.

29:59.898 --> 30:00.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I agree with Mark.

30:01.033 --> 30:03.568 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The whole presentation was just
powerful.

30:03.602 --> 30:05.370 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's funny.

30:05.404 --> 30:08.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Maybe it just because I'm tired,
but the further
away you get, the less you know
about the

30:08.473 --> 30:12.511 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
convention, and it boils down to
a core theme,
to one thing.

30:12.544 --> 30:17.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so for the Republican
Convention, I think
of Trump's speech and sort of
the darkness,

30:17.683 --> 30:23.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the fear of crime, the need for
a strong arm
really, and so that one core
theme.

30:23.488 --> 30:27.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, for the Democratic
one, I really
think of Trump erratic.

30:27.659 --> 30:29.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that was the big message
that came
out.

30:29.861 --> 30:33.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The positive agenda for Hillary
was a little
less vibrant.

30:33.398 --> 30:38.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And of those two, I do think
that the -- right
now, at least in my mind, the
Democratic theme

30:38.870 --> 30:40.839 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is eclipsing the Republican one.

30:40.872 --> 30:43.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, the Democrats won this
volley, I think.

30:43.809 --> 30:48.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Mark, we're
hearing today
that the numbers of people
watching the conventions

30:48.714 --> 30:51.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was a little bit higher for the
Republican
Convention.

30:51.817 --> 30:55.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How much do these conventions
set the stage
for the rest of this campaign?

30:55.887 --> 31:00.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it's, what, 101 days
between now and
the Election Day.

31:00.358 --> 31:04.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, if David and
I are right,
which is...

31:04.329 --> 31:06.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Ninety-nine
percent of the
time.

31:06.832 --> 31:10.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: ... a very long
shot, then Hillary
Clinton should get a bounce out
of this convention,

31:10.502 --> 31:12.404 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean a bounce in the polls.

31:12.437 --> 31:16.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's probably conceded
that Donald
Trump got about a three-point
bounce out of

31:16.575 --> 31:17.876 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his conventions.

31:17.909 --> 31:20.512 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He's closed the gap that much.

31:20.545 --> 31:24.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if she doesn't, I mean,
after what was
a good convention -- this is
when you have

31:24.983 --> 31:30.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the unfiltered message of your
party and your
candidate to the country, even a
slice of

31:30.689 --> 31:37.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the country, for four full days
-- then I
think it's some cause for alarm
for the Democrats.

31:37.262 --> 31:42.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, you know, I think what
we're looking
at next, Judy, is the debates.

31:42.834 --> 31:50.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, barring something
major, a mishap
on one side or a tragedy or a
scandal, I think,

31:50.308 --> 31:54.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you know, we're looking at the
debates, because
I think that's the kind of race
it's going

31:54.146 --> 31:56.047 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to be.

31:56.081 --> 31:58.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And they don't
start, David,
until the end of September and
then into October.

31:58.717 --> 32:04.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, do these conventions, do
they define this
race going forward?

32:04.289 --> 32:06.291 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: I think to some
degree.

32:06.324 --> 32:13.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But now it's my turn to rain on
progressive
overconfidence, because the two
weakest speeches,

32:13.765 --> 32:17.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
major ones, for the Democrats
were the two
candidates, not that they were
bad.

32:17.669 --> 32:23.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They just weren't up to the
level of Biden's,
the Obamas, and Bloomberg's
even.

32:23.275 --> 32:27.979 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so you have got two
candidates on the
Democratic side who may be
making sense, may

32:28.013 --> 32:29.314 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
agree or disagree.

32:29.347 --> 32:32.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're just not as vibrant
personalities
as Donald Trump.

32:32.450 --> 32:38.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, over the next month,
until the debates,
I expect Trump to do what he's
done very successfully,

32:38.123 --> 32:40.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is, whether you like him
or not, he
will be the dominant player
here.

32:40.959 --> 32:42.727 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He will be the one on offense.

32:42.761 --> 32:46.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He will be the one serving
volleys, and it
may be some weird stuff about
the Russians,

32:46.565 --> 32:50.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but he will be controlling
things a little
more than he probably did over
the last two

32:50.101 --> 32:51.503 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
weeks.

32:51.536 --> 32:54.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And is that now
the way elections
get decided, Mark?

32:54.606 --> 32:58.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, let me just
dissent a
little bit from David.

32:58.210 --> 33:04.216 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I think Donald Trump is
obviously the more
colorful, the more flamboyant,
the more dominant

33:04.249 --> 33:05.217 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
personality.

33:05.250 --> 33:07.018 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But take the Russia issue.

33:07.052 --> 33:10.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You open up the convention, and
you have got
a report that the Democratic
Party has been

33:10.722 --> 33:16.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hacked by the Russians, e-mails,
the e-mails
of the Democratic Party, which
is a headline

33:16.328 --> 33:19.898 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and words that you don't want,
if you're Hillary
Clinton's campaign.

33:19.931 --> 33:26.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Donald Trump immediately
takes the story
and basically steps on the
advantage he has

33:26.404 --> 33:28.740 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and say, well, the Russians, who
am I to tell
Putin?

33:28.773 --> 33:34.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, the Russians ought to
come in and
continue to hack our -- and find
out where

33:34.246 --> 33:36.114 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the e-mails are.

33:36.147 --> 33:41.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, it was -- it was wrong,
it was irresponsible,
and it was unhelpful to his
candidacy.

33:41.253 --> 33:48.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a strange way -- there are a
couple thoughts
of David that reminded me of
this -- an awful

33:48.193 --> 33:53.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lot of people don't ordinarily
have day-to-day
contact with police officers.

33:53.098 --> 33:58.603 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In both Cleveland and
Philadelphia, the police
were enormously, enormously
impressive, I

33:58.637 --> 34:01.740 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mean, their temperament, to use
a word that's
going to be central...

34:01.773 --> 34:02.974 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

34:03.008 --> 34:04.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You don't mean
the police on
the stage.

34:04.142 --> 34:05.243 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You mean the police in the
street.

34:05.277 --> 34:06.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: No, I mean the
police in the
streets.

34:06.611 --> 34:08.947 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I mean, I really -- the
interaction with the
police.

34:08.980 --> 34:10.348 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They had to be tired.

34:10.382 --> 34:15.620 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, they had a lot of
jerks, including
several in the press.

34:15.654 --> 34:17.055 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And it was hot.

34:17.088 --> 34:18.556 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It was hot.

34:18.590 --> 34:24.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they had long hours, and
they were just
so professional and so cool.

34:24.329 --> 34:28.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it strikes me that it's the
competing
pronouns that the Democrats did
effectively,

34:29.000 --> 34:30.502 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I vs. we.

34:30.535 --> 34:32.938 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's we the people.

34:32.971 --> 34:37.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Donald Trump says nobody
knows it like
me, I can do it.

34:37.108 --> 34:43.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that was a very
effective construct
in framing this race.

34:43.415 --> 34:45.150 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

34:45.183 --> 34:46.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just to pick up on the cops, we
don't really
-- I hadn't really thought about
it, but we

34:46.651 --> 34:48.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all agree they did such a good
job by not
being overaggressive.

34:48.853 --> 34:50.655 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

34:50.689 --> 34:53.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: But for Donald
Trump -- just
the political effects of that,
Donald Trump's

34:53.124 --> 34:57.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
argument is essentially it's
1968, the cities
are burning.

34:57.529 --> 35:00.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if something really bad had
happened in
one of those two cities, that
would have underlined

35:00.832 --> 35:01.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that theme.

35:01.833 --> 35:02.867 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: That's right.

35:02.901 --> 35:04.102 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: And nothing bad
happened.

35:04.135 --> 35:07.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so -- but that doesn't mean
we're not
-- it's settled.

35:07.272 --> 35:09.140 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Events are in the saddle here.

35:09.174 --> 35:14.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If ISIS really begins a sort of
continual
series of weird, random attacks
around the

35:14.612 --> 35:16.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
world, then that does underline
the theme.

35:16.815 --> 35:19.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that goes back to something
I have been
saying for the last couple of
weeks, is, we're

35:19.818 --> 35:22.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not quite sure what ball game
we're playing
here.

35:22.687 --> 35:27.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we're playing the normal
political rules,
where you want to have people
loving each

35:27.125 --> 35:32.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other, compassionate, working
together, being
generous toward each other,
being well-informed

35:32.097 --> 35:36.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about the issues, well, if those
are the rules,
then the Democrats are doing
really well.

35:36.401 --> 35:41.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if we're in some sort of
Hobbesian state
of nature, where you just want a
strong man

35:41.139 --> 35:46.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who has no compassion, who you
just want a
toughness, well, then that -- by
those rules,

35:46.978 --> 35:48.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Donald Trump is going to do a
little better.

35:48.413 --> 35:50.148 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we will figure out what game
we're playing.

35:50.181 --> 35:53.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Which is what the
Democrats
were trying to say for three or
four days

35:53.485 --> 35:56.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- for four days, Mark, which,
is, we don't
need this.

35:56.054 --> 35:57.489 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We're a strong people.

35:57.522 --> 36:00.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're a good people and we don't
need some
bully telling us what to do.

36:00.392 --> 36:01.359 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: No, exactly.

36:01.393 --> 36:03.061 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the president did that, I
thought.

36:03.094 --> 36:04.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
President Obama did.

36:04.829 --> 36:09.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a strange way, Hillary
Clinton was helped
and victimized by Mr. and Mrs.
Obama.

36:09.701 --> 36:11.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think Michelle Obama gave a
speech...

36:11.703 --> 36:12.670 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Victimized?

36:12.704 --> 36:14.506 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Really?

36:14.539 --> 36:17.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, politically,
because they
were just -- you were talking
about -- I mean,

36:17.776 --> 36:21.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Michelle Obama was probably
better than Barack
Obama, if you think about it.

36:21.679 --> 36:24.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Her speech is a masterful,
masterful speech.

36:24.315 --> 36:29.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And she delivered it in a
persuasively conversational
tone.

36:29.354 --> 36:34.325 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You can't say this is a
political attack or
a political document.

36:34.359 --> 36:40.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was just -- so, in a strange
way, she's
getting compared to -- instead
of to Donald

36:40.265 --> 36:45.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump, she's being compared to
Joe Biden,
who gave this emotional
valedictory about

36:45.870 --> 36:51.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
America and his life, and both
Obamas, who
were dominant.

36:51.409 --> 36:55.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tim Kaine reminds me of -- Peter
Hart, the
pollster, has a question when he
asks about

36:55.980 --> 37:00.151 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
presidential or vice
presidential candidates,
what kind of a neighbor would
they be?

37:00.185 --> 37:04.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And several Democrats -- George
W. Bush was
always seen to be a good
friendly neighbor

37:04.189 --> 37:08.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who would pick up the newspapers
if you were
out of town or check your mail.

37:08.426 --> 37:10.728 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Tim Kaine is a good neighbor.

37:10.762 --> 37:14.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's kind of the dependable, you
know, friendly,
helpful.

37:14.766 --> 37:17.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, you know, he would be over
there.

37:17.902 --> 37:21.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He would give you a hand if
there were a problem
at the house.

37:21.639 --> 37:23.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But does that
help Hillary
Clinton?

37:23.675 --> 37:25.477 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

37:25.510 --> 37:28.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: It does, because
it gives Hillary
Clinton -- what they didn't
address at this

37:28.146 --> 37:34.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
convention is Hillary Clinton's
problems of
her personality and her secrecy.

37:34.152 --> 37:35.987 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They tried through testimony.

37:36.020 --> 37:38.022 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She just can't open up herself.

37:38.056 --> 37:39.724 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She can't make fun of herself.

37:39.757 --> 37:43.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She can't be self-deprecating,
or at least,
if she can, she wasn't, made the
decision

37:43.461 --> 37:44.929 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not to be.

37:44.963 --> 37:48.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so Tim Kaine kind of gives
the warmer,
human face of the Democrats.

37:48.633 --> 37:52.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: But if she's
elected, this will
be an issue and this will be a
problem for

37:52.103 --> 37:53.872 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
her.

37:53.905 --> 37:56.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's important for presidents to
emotionally
connect, with the country in
times of crisis,

37:56.841 --> 37:58.910 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
but also with people in
Washington.

37:58.943 --> 38:03.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you can't emotionally connect
-- and Obama
is not the greatest, but he can
at least do

38:03.381 --> 38:06.851 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it -- then people won't be with
you when the
times are hard.

38:06.885 --> 38:11.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There will just always be a
distance between
you and the people around you.

38:11.156 --> 38:14.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, she can clearly emotionally
connect with
her intimates within the zone of
trust.

38:14.792 --> 38:19.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just the wall outside the
zone of trust
is so impermeable.

38:19.297 --> 38:23.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I do think -- I was
really struck,
like every pundit, from Mark and
I on down...

38:23.234 --> 38:25.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, on down,
